  "text": "Our data analysis of HLA class I genes (-A and -B) suggest an association between HLA-A*26 and an increased risk to leptospirosis. This result does not validate previously reported associations of HLA-A*24, HLA-A*31 and HLA-B*08 alleles with leptospirosis performed in the Azorean island of Terceira [CITATION_1] . However, due to (1) the limited number of individuals carrying these particular combinations of specific HLA molecules and (2) large confidence interval values obtained from statistical analysis, this may not be a reliable association risk. Extended HLA-A and -B haplotypes did not reveal any association either. Interestingly, in Xue's study [CITATION_2] , the genes involved in antigen processing and presentation pathways in MPMs and HBMs were mainly downregulated, and the down regulations in HBMs were more significant than those in MPMs. Taken together, these findings suggest that probably HLA genes are not directly associated with host defence against Leptospira.",
